      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You should consider a registered survey before selling if there is any doubt about where your legal boundary sits, if structures like fences, sheds, or decks appear to be close to the boundary line, or if you are aware of a past dispute with a neighbour about the boundary. The cost of a registered survey in Brisbane is typically between $1,500 and $3,000 depending on the lot size and complexity."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a boundary encroachment and how does it affect a Brisbane property sale?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A boundary encroachment is when a structure such as a fence, building, eaves, or deck crosses the legal boundary onto an adjoining lot. Encroachments must be disclosed if the seller is aware of them. Buyers' solicitors and building inspectors routinely identify encroachments, and undisclosed known encroachments can give buyers grounds to seek a price reduction or terminate the contract."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How are boundary encroachments resolved when selling a Brisbane property?",
