      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Property Surveys and Boundary Issues When Selling in Brisbane
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Boundary issues are among the more common complications in Brisbane property sales. Fences that moved over the decades, sheds built close to the line, and decks that were never fully checked against the registered plan all create disclosure obligations and negotiation risk that sellers are better off understanding before campaign day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's inner east is full of properties that have been bought, sold, renovated, and added to over sixty or seventy years without anyone ever verifying that the fence running along the back boundary still aligns with the legal title. In most cases, it does. In a meaningful number, it does not. The difference matters when a buyer's solicitor or building inspector raises it mid-contract, and it matters a great deal if it surfaces post-settlement when the seller is no longer in a position to manage it easily.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a property survey actually is</h2>
      <p>A registered survey is conducted by a licensed cadastral surveyor who physically marks and records the legal boundaries of your lot on the ground. The surveyor uses the registered title plan, any existing survey marks, and the surrounding cadastral network to determine where the boundaries sit. The result is a survey plan that shows the legal boundary, the location of existing structures relative to it, and any encroachments in either direction.</p>

      <p>A registered survey is different from a building and pest inspection. A building inspector will identify structural issues, pest damage, and obvious construction problems. They are not licensed cadastral surveyors and are not providing a legal opinion on where the boundary sits. If boundary certainty matters for your sale, a registered survey is the appropriate instrument.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to consider commissioning one before listing</h2>
      <p>Not every property needs a new survey before sale. For straightforward lots with no history of boundary disputes, no structures close to the line, and no concerns raised by neighbours, proceeding without one is reasonable. The cost of a registered survey in Brisbane ranges from around $1,500 to $3,000 or more depending on the lot size, terrain, and complexity.</p>

      <p>A survey is worth commissioning before listing when any of the following apply: there is genuine uncertainty about where the boundary sits, particularly at the back or side where fences may have been moved over time; a structure (shed, pool, deck, garage, retaining wall) is close to the boundary and may or may not be within the lot; a neighbouring property has been developed or subdivided in a way that could have affected the shared boundary; or a previous sale or renovation flagged a potential boundary issue that was never formally resolved.</p>

      <p>Commissioning the survey yourself, before going to market, gives you control over the information. You know what it shows, you can address any issue before buyers discover it, and you are not managing a surprise that surfaces through a buyer's due diligence process when you have less flexibility to respond.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a boundary encroachment is and what to do about it</h2>
      <p>A boundary encroachment is when a structure crosses the legal boundary onto the adjoining lot. Common examples in Brisbane's inner east include a fence that has drifted three or four years over time (timber fences on older lots shift with the ground and are frequently not in their original position), eaves or guttering from a structure near the boundary that overhang into the neighbouring property, a shed or garage that was built without a survey and turns out to sit partly on the neighbour's land, and decks or pergolas built close to the side boundary that were not checked against the registered plan before construction.</p>

      <p>Queensland sellers who are aware of a boundary encroachment must disclose it. The obligation is not triggered by the fact that an encroachment might exist if someone looked carefully enough. It is triggered by the seller's actual knowledge. If you know the fence was moved by the previous owner and sits on the neighbour's land, that is a known encroachment. If you have never thought about it and have no reason to suspect one, you do not have an obligation to commission a survey to find out. The distinction is important, but sellers in the first category should not try to squeeze into the second.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How encroachments are resolved</h2>
      <p>The resolution path depends on the nature and severity of the encroachment, the relationship between the neighbours, and what the buyer requires as a condition of proceeding with the purchase. Common resolution options include a formal boundary adjustment, where both landowners agree to change the registered boundary and lodge the adjustment with the titles registry; registration of an encroachment easement, which formalises the encroachment without changing the boundary; removal of the encroaching structure before settlement; and a negotiated financial settlement that compensates the affected party without requiring a structural change.</p>

      <p>Not all encroachments require the same response. A fence that sits thirty centimetres into a neighbouring property may be resolved through an easement or a boundary adjustment relatively simply, provided both neighbours agree. A garage that encroaches significantly and involves a structural remediation creates a more complex negotiation. The point is that these issues are manageable when they are identified and addressed before going to market. They are considerably more difficult to manage when they surface mid-contract with a buyer who has already committed to finance and building inspection costs and expects the matter resolved before settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the registered plan shows versus what a current survey reveals</h2>
      <p>The registered plan for your lot is a historical document. It reflects the boundaries as surveyed and registered at the time the lot was created. Over the decades since then, fences have been rebuilt not quite in the same place, vegetation has grown, structures have been added, and neighbouring lots have been developed. A current survey reveals what is actually on the ground relative to the legal boundary today, not what was on the ground when the registered plan was prepared.</p>

      <p>Buyers' solicitors and building inspectors sometimes identify discrepancies between the registered plan and the physical layout of the property. If the discrepancy involves a structure that appears to encroach, it will be raised. If you have already had a survey done and can provide a clear answer, the matter is resolved quickly. If you have not, the buyer may request a survey as a contract condition, and the process then runs on the buyer's timeline rather than yours.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Title insurance and boundary disputes</h2>
      <p>Title insurance policies vary in their coverage, and some do include protection for boundary encroachments that were unknown at the time of purchase. Sellers should not rely on the existence of a title insurance policy as a reason not to disclose a known encroachment, and buyers should not assume that title insurance resolves all boundary risk. The policy terms and the specific circumstances determine what is covered. Legal advice from a property solicitor is the appropriate source of guidance on whether a title insurance policy provides relevant cover for a specific encroachment situation.</p>

